SIMPLE: pasquin
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pasquin
<hw>Pas"quin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.
<ets>pasquino</ets> a mutilated statue at Rome, set up against the wall
of the place of the Orsini; -- so called from a witty cobbler or tailor,
near whose shop the statue was dug up. On this statue it was customary
to paste satiric papers.]</ety> <def>A lampooner; also, a lampoon. See
<er>Pasquinade</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Grecian wits, who satire first began,⟦br⟧
Were pleasant <qex>pasquins</qex> on the life of man.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pasquin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pasquin
<hw>Pas"quin</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To lampoon; to satiraze.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To see himself <qex>pasquined</qex> and affronted.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pasquinade</ent>⟦br⟧
